
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `enc2xs` baraye dorost kardane module-haye Perl baraye encoding-haye jadid estefade mishavad. Yani shoma mitavanid ba estefade az in dastoor, encoding-haye khassi ke Perl be soorat pishfarz poshtibani nemikonad ra be an ezafe konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-o <directory>`  --> 📂 Mahal-e zakhire-ye file-haye sakhte shode ra moshakhas mikonad.
    🔹 `-n <module_name>` --> 🏷️ Name module-e jadid ra tayin mikonad.
    🔹 `-f <encoding_file>` --> 📄 File-i ke etela'at encoding dar an zakhire shode ra moshakhas mikonad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ enc2xs -o Encode::MyEncoding -n MyEncoding my_encoding.enc

    🔹 Module-e Encode::MyEncoding ra ba estefade az etela'at dar file my_encoding.enc dorost mikonad.

    $ enc2xs -o lib -n ShamEncoding sham.enc

    🔹 Module-e ShamEncoding ra dorost mikonad va an ra dar directory 'lib' zakhire mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ enc2xs -n FarsiEncoding farsi.enc

    🔹 Module-e FarsiEncoding az file `farsi.enc` sakhte mishavad. File `farsi.enc` bayad format-e munasibi dashte bashad ta `enc2xs` betavanad an ra be dorosti pars konad va module ra besazad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `enc2xs` command is used to build Perl modules for new encodings.  This allows you to add custom encodings that Perl doesn't natively support.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-o <directory>`  --> 📂 Specifies the directory where the generated files will be stored.
    🔹 `-n <module_name>` --> 🏷️ Sets the name of the new module.
    🔹 `-f <encoding_file>` --> 📄 Specifies the file containing the encoding information.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ enc2xs -o Encode::MyEncoding -n MyEncoding my_encoding.enc

    🔹 Creates the Encode::MyEncoding module using the information from the my_encoding.enc file.

    $ enc2xs -o lib -n ShamEncoding sham.enc

    🔹 Creates the ShamEncoding module and stores it in the 'lib' directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ enc2xs -n FarsiEncoding farsi.enc

    🔹 A module called `FarsiEncoding` is created based on the data from the `farsi.enc` file. The `farsi.enc` file must be in the correct format for `enc2xs` to parse it and create the module properly.
